bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: Friendship House was founded in 1904, and continues today as an active settlement house and neighborhood center in Southeast. It has been described as the oldest and largest settlement house and social service agency in Washington. It was founded with the goal to help those in need to become socially and economically self-reliant. Also Friendship House served as a community center and meeting place for the area. It became in the latter half of the century a conduit to administer social service programs instituted by the city and federal government, and by large private agencies such as United Way. Friendship House had its roots as Rochefort House, begun by a group of young unmarried women who were inspired by the writings of the reformer Jacob Riis. Miss Lydia Burklin began working with the group, and from 1904 until her death in 1964 she devoted all her physical and monetary resources to the project. The house had five rented locations until 1916, when the organization was given deed to 326-328 Virginia Avenue. In 1937 they were able to move to a larger place, their present location. "The Maples" is one of the oldest houses in Washington and is at 619 D Street SE. Generous gifts enabled the organization to add on a theater and annex adjacent property. Miss Burklin lived on the premises for many years and then was given a house nearby. Miss Burklin was able to attract financial help from Washington's businesses and social elite. Friendship House conversely was able to serve this larger constituency by providing an outlet for the charitable volunteer impulses of society women, Congressmen's wives, and also professional social workers , nursery school teachers, musical instructors, etc.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection contains meeting minutes, correspondence, reports, committee records, newspapers, and other materials associated with the work of this organization. The records are administrative and financial and describe many of the activities and interests of Friendship House. The most consistent and comprehensive record of Friendship House's history is in the minutes of the Board of Directors. There are monthly meeting notes from 1904 to 1985. The Friendship House papers cover the years 1904-92.

The papers of Friendship House, a settlement house in southeast Washington DC, were acquired as a part of the Washingtoniana Collection by Gelman Library, Department of Special Collections. The Friendship House papers were arranged and processed under a grant from the National Historic Publications and Records Commission. The grant, entitled "Washington's Hometown History" was granted in the fall of 1990 but actually was not implemented until April of 1991. The one year grant for an archivist, supplies and student assistance, saw the majority of the work completed by June 1992. Because of the volume of the materials to be processed (165 cartons) additional funding was secured from the Mason Fund for completion of the project. The Friendship House papers project was completed in January 1993.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized in seven series: Historical materials, Adminstration, Activities, Financial records, Funding sources, Other organizations, and Oversized records.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs, rental agreements, constitutions, bylaws, certificates of incorporation, deeds, factsheets, sketches, correspondence, brochures, maps, postcards, newspaper clippings, histories, reports, fliers, blueprints, publications, floorplans, programs and guest lists. This material dates from 1904 to 1990 with some materials undated. The bulk of the collection material covers 1912 -81.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains programs, photographs, reports, forms, brochures, and newspaper/magazine clippings and document various programs and activities of the Friendship House Association. The material dates from 1919 to 1990 with the bulk of the collection materials dated in the 1960s.

Of particular interest in this series are the records which relate to the the various child care/recreational/educational programs operated by the Friendship House Association. Friendship had child care programs from almost its earliest years. The programs were deemed necessary for working mothers and women who were ill. Sometimes children even stayed at Friendship House pending location of foster homes or adoption. During the War and after many women worked in DC at office jobs to free men for the Armed Services, so the programs were even more necessary (see folder 13). These programs continue to the present.

Two of the longest lasting volunteer groups at Friendship House were the Congressional Circle, made up of women associated with government and wives of Congressmen, and the Circle on the Hill which was a Women's Club from the Capitol Hill area. These groups sponsored some of the biggest fund raisers for Friendship House, notably Market Day. Market Day was a street fair, which goes on to the present time, now sponsored by Friendship House itself.

Friendship House reached out into the community and sponsored programs in the neighborhood public housing projects. They brought the same programs held in the House itself to these areas, among them the Arthur Capper project and the Potomac Gardens.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains newspapers, reports, budgets, and grant proposals which document supplemental funding for the Friendship House Association. The materials cover the dates 1940-81. The bulk of the collection materials is dated from 1965-79.

The longest continuous funding to Friendship House was from the United Way. It was the only large agency funding in the early years. It was a funder of Friendship House from its earliest years of its existence. The previous names for the United Way agency were The Community Chest (sometimes called Red Feather Campaign), United Community Services, United Givers Fund, and finally United Way. In addition to these materials are records relating to support provided by the United Planning Organization. United Planning Organization: Neighborhood Development Program 1964-81, Neighborhood Advisory Committee 1965-81, Neighborhood Legal Service 1965-69, Consumer Action Program 1965-78, Neighborhood Development Youth Program 1966-68, Community Organization Unit 1970-82, VISTA 1965-67, Community Action Program 1966-76, Head Start 1966-69.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains newspapers, newsletters, programs, brochures, correspondence, and reports which document the Friendship House Association's involvement with local, regional, and national organizations. The materials in this series cover the dates 1923-81. The bulk of the collection materials are dated from 1960-75.

Because so many Friendship House programs were child-oriented, the DC Schools were involved in formulating their programs, and likewise certain school programs and problems were discussed by Friendship House. Friendship House was involved in school policies and problems, especially of those in the neighborhood. Of particular interest in this series are records related to other Settlement Houses.
